#Text=Jacqueline de Longwy
#Text=Jacqueline de
#Text=Longwy , Countess of Bar-sur-Seine
#Text=( before 1520 – 28 August 1561 ) , Duchess of Montpensier , Dauphine of Auvergne was a French noblewoman , and a half-niece of King Francis I of France .
#Text=She was the first wife of Louis III de Bourbon , Duke of Montpensier , and the mother of his six children .
#Text=She had the office of Première dame d'honneur to the queen dowager regent of France , Catherine de ' Medici , from 1560 until 1561 .
#Text=Family

#Text=Jacqueline was born on an unknown date sometime before 1520 , the youngest daughter of Jean IV de Longwy , Seigneur de Givry , Baron of Pagny and of Mirebeau ( died 1520 ) and Jeanne of Angoulême , Countess of Bar-sur-Seine ( c.1490- after 1531/1538 ) , the illegitimate half-sister of King Francis I of France .
#Text=Jacqueline had two older sisters .

#Text=The eldest , Françoise de Longwy , Dame de Pagny and de Mirebeau ( c.1510- after 14 April 1561 ) , married firstly in 1526 , Philippe de Chabot , Seigneur De Brion , Count of Charny and Buzançois , Admiral of France , and secondly in 1545 , Jacques de Perusse , Seigneur d'Escars , by whom she had a son , Cardinal Anne d'Escars de Givry .
#Text=Her second eldest sister was Claude Louise de Longwy , Abbess of Jouarre .
#Text=Jacqueline 's paternal uncle was Claude de Longwy de Givry , Bishop of Amiens .
#Text=Her paternal grandparents were Philippe de Longwy , Seigneur of Pagny and Jeanne de Bauffremont , Dame de Mirebeau .

#Text=Her maternal grandparents were Charles , Count of Angoulême and his mistress Antoinette de Polignac , Dame de Combronde , who was a lady-in-waiting to the Count of Angoulême 's wife , Louise of Savoy . Antoinette ( born c.1460 ) was the daughter of Foucaud de Polignac , Seigneur des Fontaines and Agnès de Chabanais .
#Text=Marriage
#Text=In 1538 , Jacqueline married Louis III de Bourbon-Montpensier , [ 1 ] who would become Duke of Montpensier on the death of his mother Louise de Bourbon , Duchess of Montpensier on 5 July 1561 .
#Text=On the occasion of the marriage , Jacqueline 's uncle , King Francis restored the Montpensier estates and the counties of Forez , Beaujeu , and Dombes to Louis ' mother .
#Text=They had been confiscated by the French Crown following Charles III , Duke of Bourbon ' s treason in 1523 when he defected to the side of Emperor Charles V .
#Text=Court career
#Text=Jacqueline de Longwy was introduced at court , which she attended from 1533 onward .
#Text=She became a personal friend of Catherine de ' Medici , who became queen in 1547 .

#Text=In 1560 , Jacqueline de Longwy had been instrumental in the successful negotiations to convince Antoine de Bourbon to relinquish his claims to the regency of Charles in favor of Catherine de ' Medici . [ 2 ]

#Text=She was subsequently appointed Première dame d'honneur and head of the queen 's ladies-in-waiting , when Catherine became regent and was able to appoint her own household , in succession to Françoise de Brézé . [ 2 ]
#Text=Countess of Bar-sur-Seine
#Text=Jacqueline succeeded to the title of suo jure Countess of Bar-sur-Seine upon her mother 's death , which occurred on an unknown date sometime after 1531/1538 .
#Text=Her father 's titles had passed to her eldest sister , Françoise upon his death in 1520 .
#Text=In 1543 , the dauphinate of Auvergne was restored to Louis , Jacqueline therefore became the Dauphine of Auvergne .
#Text=That same year , she was present with other high-ranking members of the Valois court at the baptism of King Francis 's grandson , Francis .
#Text=In 1547 , King Francis died and was succeeded by his son Henry .

#Text=In 1556 , Jacqueline , together with Diane de Poitiers and Madame de Montmorency , was appointed by Queen consort Catherine de Medici to judge the case of misconduct against Mademoiselle de Rohan , a member of the royal family , who was pregnant by the Duke of Nemours under promise of marriage .
#Text=Three years later , in 1559 , Jacqueline and her husband attended the magnificent coronation of King Francis II and Mary , Queen of Scots .
#Text=Death
#Text=She died in Paris on 28 August 1561 .
#Text=She had been the Duchess of Montpensier for less than two months .

#Text=Through her daughter , Charlotte , Jacqueline was an ancestress of the House of Hanover , which reigned in Great Britain from 1714 to 1901 , and from which descends the current British Royal Family .
#Text=Issue
#Text=The marriage of Jacqueline and Louis produced one son and five daughters :
#Text=François de Bourbon , Duke of Montpensier

#Text=( 1542- 4 June 1592 ) , married in 1566 , Renée d'Anjou , Marquise de Mézières ( 21 October 1550- 1597 ) , daughter of Nicolas d'Anjou , Marquis de Mézières and Gabrielle de Mareuil , by whom he had one son , Henri de Bourbon , Duke of Montpensier .
#Text=Françoise de Bourbon ( 1539 – 1587 ) , in 1559 married Henri Robert de La Marck ( de la Marck ) , Duke of Bouillon , Prince of Sedan
#Text=Anne de Bourbon ( 1540 1577 ) , in 1561 married François de Cleves , Duke of Nevers
#Text=Jeanne de Bourbon , Abbess of Jouarre ( 1541 – 1620 )
#Text=Charlotte de Bourbon ( 1547- 5 May 1582 ) , [ 1 ] on 24 June 1575 , married William The Silent of Nassau , Prince of Orange , by whom she had six daughters
#Text=Louise de Bourbon , Abbess of Faremoutier ( 1548 – 1586 )
#Text=In art
#Text=Jacqueline de Longwy 's portrait was drawn in 1550 by French painter François Clouet .
